SIMPLE: stray
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stray
<hw>Stray</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Strayed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Straying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>estraier</ets>,
<ets>estraer</ets>, to stray, or as adj., stray, fr. (assumed) L.
<ets>stratarius</ets> roving the streets, fr. L. <ets>strata</ets> (sc.
<ets>via</ets>) a paved road. See <er>Street</er>, and <er>Stray</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wander, as from a direct
course; to deviate, or go out of the way.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thames among the wanton valleys <qex>strays</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wander from company, or from the proper limits;
to rove at large; to roam; to go astray.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now, until the break of day,⟦br⟧
Through this house each fairy <qex>stray</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sheep doth very often <qex>stray</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Figuratively, to wander from the path of duty or
rectitude; to err.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have erred and <qex>strayed</qex> from thy ways.</q>
<rj><qau><?/<?/<?/ of Com. Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While meaner things, whom instinct leads,⟦br⟧
Are rarely known to <qex>stray</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To deviate; err; swerve; rove; roam;
wander.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stray
<hw>Stray</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to stray.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stray
<hw>Stray</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>estrai⟦eacute⟧</ets>,
p. p. of <ets>estraier</ets>. See <er>Stray</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Astray</er>, <er>Estray</er>.]</ety> <def>Having gone astray;
strayed; wandering; <as>as, a <ex>stray</ex>horse or
sheep</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stray line</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>that portion
of the log line which is veered from the reel to allow the chip to get
clear of the stern eddies before the glass is turned.</cd> --
<col><b>Stray mark</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the mark indicating
the end of the stray line.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stray
<hw>Stray</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any domestic animal that
has an inclosure, or its proper place and company, and wanders at large,
or is lost; an estray. Used also figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seeing him wander about, I took him up for a <qex>stray</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of wandering or going astray.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1424 --></p>

<p><ent>Strayer</ent>⟦br⟧
